{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489379"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:14:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:14:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"645"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/645"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.22,0.17,0.53,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"645"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115156"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/645"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"645"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97164"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"493"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48765"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115156"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of rapid palpitations, shortness of breath and gradually increasing drowsiness. He has experienced similar symptoms intermittently over the previous two months. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His regular medications are ramipril and dapagliflozin. He does not have any chest pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 140/min and regular, blood pressure 95/55 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. An urgent ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral digoxin","Intravenous bolus of adenosine","Amiodarone infusion","Synchronised electrical cardioversion","Radiofrequency flutter ablation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with atrial flutter and evidence of haemodynamic compromise (hypotension and altered mental status). The ECG shows the classic saw-tooth flutter waves most prominent in leads II, III, and aVF, with 2:1 atrioventricular block resulting in a ventricular rate of approximately 150 beats per minute.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynchronised electrical cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E is the treatment of choice for patients with atrial flutter who are haemodynamically unstable. This rapidly and effectively terminates the arrhythmia and should be performed immediately after brief sedation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral digoxin\u003C/strong\u003E is a rate control medication that would be inappropriate in this emergency situation. It has a slow onset of action and would not address the immediate need to restore haemodynamic stability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous adenosine\u003C/strong\u003E can be used diagnostically to reveal underlying flutter waves by causing transient AV block, but it is not a definitive treatment for atrial flutter and would be inappropriate in an unstable patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmiodarone infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is a rhythm control option for stable patients with atrial flutter but takes time to work and would not address the immediate haemodynamic compromise in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiofrequency flutter ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is an excellent option for preventing recurrence of atrial flutter but is not an emergency treatment. This would be considered as an elective procedure after the acute episode has been managed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atrial flutter with hypotension and altered mental status requires immediate synchronised electrical cardioversion","The key ECG features of atrial flutter are saw-tooth flutter waves (best seen in leads II, III, aVF) and regular narrow complex tachycardia with 2:1 block","Medical management of atrial flutter is appropriate only in haemodynamically stable patients"],"references":["Page R, Joglar J, Caldwell M, Calkins H, Conti J, Deal B et al. 2015 ACC/AHA/HRS Guideline for the Management of Adult Patients With Supraventricular Tachycardia. Circulation. 2016;133(14)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97164"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"645"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22133"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22133"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8KaSAZZhZHeI9kYqa0C7NQ8OkX0gq0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8KaSAZZhZHeI9kYqa0C7NQ8OkX0gq0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":341}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevi